It may be also that the rains are more frequent at its source in that season, because the etesian blasts of the north winds drive all the clouds together into those parts at that time. And, you are to know, when they have been driven on to the central region of day and have gathered together, then the clouds jammed close against the high mountains are massed together and violently compressed. Perhaps too it gets its in- crease high up from the lofty mountains of the Ethiopians, when the all- surveying sun with his thawing rays constrains the white snows to descend into the plains.
